 prose sources, incidents and people from whom the poet drew inspiration, and structural and stylistic analysis. Mimic Fires provides a historical overview, a retrospective conclusion, and an extensive bibliography, and is informed throughout by ecopoetic, feminist, new historicist, and post-colonial theories. By improving our understanding of nineteenth-century Canadian writing, Mimic Fires in turn affects how we view writing in Canada in this century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanada dans la littérature. 0aCanadian poetry (English)xHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aCanadian poetry (English)xHistory and criticismxTo 1867. 0aNarrative poetry, Canadian (English)xHistory and criticism. 0aPoésie canadienne-anglaisexHistoire et critiquex19e siècle. 0aPoésie canadienne-anglaisexHistoire et critiquexAvant 1867. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356481740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773564817423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773564817/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles